  "dateModified": "2025-04-13",
  "datePublished": "2025-04-13",
  "description": "Media artifacts that model survivable identity postures within contradictory or collapsing systems, distributing templates for how to be a coherent actor when inherited identity models no longer function. Unlike media that entertains, explains, or persuades, socially ontogenic media provides its audience with a usable template for how to *be* inside a system that does not offer clear guidance on who to be. The mechanism is the modulation loop: a rhythmic, repeatable pattern of affective response that the audience can emulate and internalize. The category recurs across wildly different genres (Kipling's 'If—,' M*A*S*H, Phineas and Ferb) because the function — modeling survivable being under contradiction — is independent of tone.",
  "name": "Socially ontogenic media",
